// This will return true because str1 and str2 now refer to the same object
System.out.println(str1 == str2);
```
3. When you need to perform a performance-critical operation and you are confident that the strings you are comparing have the same object reference. In this case, you can use a combination of `==` and `equals()` to achieve better performance.

In summary, use `equals()` to compare strings in Java, and use `==` cautiously when comparing strings or only when you have a specific reason to do so.

